A heavily armed SWAT team bursts into your house at 2 am. They fire wooden pellets that go through the walls. They break every window in the entire house (and garage!) and continue to destroy the house even after knowing they had made a mistake. They handcuff you, and your teenage kids and drag you out of the house, even though you don’t resist and have no idea what’s going on. They later tell your daughter that they are looking for “guns and drugs” but the arrest warrant being executed is for a particular person accused of a crime who doesn’t even live at the address and isn’t a family member. You later learn the police knew the actual whereabouts of the (actually innocent) “perp.” Worse, the entire basis of the arrest warrant turns out to be false. Yet, they destroy your home, leaving you without power and water for days. The city manager later, in the newspaper but not to you, says “sorry” for the mistake, but doesn’t make any effort to even contact your family. The mayor expresses regrets—but not to you. The police chief is placed (reportedly) on admin leave. The home is destroyed and must be repaired. What should the consequences be? What is the remedy? Press conference Wednesday, at The Buzbee Law Firm, 75th floor, 600 Travis, downtown Houston, 11 am.  The family will be present.

After Hurricane Harvey devastated his house, homeowner Emilio Menchaca made a claim on his insurance. He was told his damage claim was less than his 6k deductible and thus received nothing. The Insurance company later sued homeowner Menchaca. They claimed he failed to “comply” with his policy. They wanted the court to declare they were in compliance with the insurance policy and Menchaca was not. Suing a policy holding homeowner is a typical bullying tactic of insurance companies when they want to scare policy holders to not challenge the underpayment of a claim. We tried multiple times to get the case against Mr. Menchaca dismissed but the judge denied our repeated requests. The insurance company lawyer at one point told my young associate that they really didn’t want to “besmirch” the Buzbee Law Firm’s name, but if Mr. Menchaca wouldn’t pay 25k to the insurance company to settle, they intended to seek at trial more than $75k in fees and they intended to assert a lien on Mr. Menchaca’s house when they obtained a judgment. As you can imagine this terrified Mr. Menchaca. His entire net worth is his house. It’s really all he owns. The gall of this particular insurance company and the outrageousness of this behavior royally pissed me off. I became involved. We picked a great jury in Galveston County on Monday and by Friday at close of business that jury found that Mr. Menchaca fully complied with his insurance policy, but the insurance company failed to comply and also acted in bad faith with regard to his insurance claim. The total jury award of $863,000 included $600,000 in past mental anguish to Mr. Menchaca and $250,000 in attorneys fees for his troubles. I asked the insurance company’s legal team when I became involved if they really wanted to try this case or if we could instead just all walk away. They smugly insisted on a trial. Fuck around, find out.

Our firm has been hired as lead counsel in this matter. I will soon be spending considerable time in west Texas. This will be a landmark case, with the hope being changing the way we tolerate the aftermath of oil and gas extraction. There are thousands of unplugged or negligently plugged wells across our state. When a plugged and abandoned well fails, the pollution to the surface and to groundwater is permanent. All across west Texas there are wide swaths of barren land due to improperly plugged wells where even grass won’t grow, and the water is so polluted it would make you immediately sick if you were to drink it.  We all value the oil and gas industry; it’s one of the primary economic drivers of our great state. However, it simply ain’t right to rape the land and leave the surface land owner with polluted water and worthless land, all because the oil and gas companies refuse to follow the standards clearly set out by the State of Texas and the Railroad Commission. My client, Ashley Watt, is a Marine combat veteran, Naval Academy grad, Harvard MBA, and owner of 22,000 acres in Crane and Ward counties. Her family’s ranch has been decimated by oil and gas production, which as surface owner and water rights owner only, her family never financially benefitted from. She is now leading the charge for accountability, and I’m proud to represent her and lead the impressive team of professionals she has assembled.

I’m often asked by lawyers across the country to step into a catastrophic case, on the eve of trial, and act as lead counsel for trial. Early in my career I tried many cases. Back then, the defense strategy was to bury us with paper, try to outspend us, and overwhelm our little firm with resources and personnel. Obviously, we ain’t little anymore, and now no firm  in the country has more resources to prosecute a big case for the injured than our team. When the insurance companies figured out we rarely lose—and instead usually win big—most of the cases I personally get involved in settle pretty quickly, on very favorable terms for our clients. There have been a few exceptions, where a large company or insurance company wants to take a chance and roll the dice. Perhaps this is one?!? We will be trying this important case for this beautiful child, horribly burned due to an automotive defect, in the next two weeks. The case will be tried in Federal Court in South Carolina. We are watching the slow decline of our society. It's terribly sad; we are all to blame. The values and principles we celebrated and collectively believed made our society strong, are crumbling. We can really do nothing about it. At some point we will be back the way we started—every human for himself, war each against everyone. Every concept we hoped or believed made us strong as a society is now vilified. We’ve become so numbed by school violence, mass shootings, greed, malfeasance, and government corruption/incompetence that we hardly notice it anymore. We ignore or tune the decline out, yet it surrounds us. It took 1000 years for the great Roman empire to collapse. But now with social media and our ability to immediately communicate, these conveniences have vastly accelerated our own decline. Those coveting from the outside used to look at the U.S. as a beacon of something good and strong. Now, I hate to say, we're held up as a bad example, and in some places laughed at. When a formerly strong society loses its collective will, and the shared beliefs in certain principles and ideas of what we thought to be “good” or “true” are abandoned, the entire framework crumbles. This is what we're seeing now. Corruption, incompetence, selfishness, hatefulness and indifference: the list goes on. But, ultimately school shootings are a symptom of this decline; these heinous assaults on our children are symbolically an attack on our country's future. What we collectively proudly built will ultimately and unfortunately die. When a large enough segment of society begins to attack the fiber of that very society, it inevitably crumbles from within. Our ability to communicate without limit, with a social media component that enforces and reinforces selfishness, vapidness and frivolity accelerates this process. We are ultimately going the way of Rome—a grand and noble idea that lasted a bit, but ended up on the trash heap of history. Maybe I am, at the moment, frustrated and angry. I’m not dumb enough, unfortunately, to simplify it all and blame guns, mental health, the current administration, China, or Russia. That would be very easy, but too easy. I’m just mad. And SAD.

Scott Higgins, deceased; father, son, friend, coworker—one of those guys who did what was needed. A good, solid person. Meticulous. He had a dry wit. He was detailed. Responsible. A guy who could always be counted upon. Scott was one of the good guys. He took extra good care of his daughters. He was devoted to his family, to his friends, to his job. He cared. When something needed to be done, the constant refrain was, “call Scott.” Scott was a veteran Marathon machinist. He worked for BP before Marathon purchased the Texas City refinery. Contrary to what Marathon Petroleum has recently said, Scott was burned to his ultimate death, at the Marathon Texas City plant, on May 15, 2023. Marathon, claims he didn’t actually die at the plant. He unfortunately did. Scott died because Marathon preferred to patch problems rather than fix them; Marathon cut corners for cash flow and Scott paid the ultimate price. Marathon put its profits over worker safety.  Scott and his family paid for Marathon’s greed. We will hold a press conference on the 75th floor of Chase Tower, Houston,  at 10 am, this Friday, May 19th. We will be suing Marathon and the other entities responsible for this good man’s death. Scott’s death was completely unnecessary and preventable. God bless him and his family. Since our historic victory in the Texas “trial of the century,” I’ve been asked repeatedly by young lawyers what the secret is to success. My answer remains the same and it won’t change. The answer? Hard work. There are no shortcuts. There is no secret sauce. No matter your chosen field, the only sure-fire way to put yourself in a position to succeed is to work hard. 

I’ve tried many big cases in my career. I’ve won almost all of them. Typically the heavy lifting is done alone in a room, late at night and in the wee hours of the morning, long before you stand up to talk in court. The Paxton case was a bit different. There certainly was a lot of work done before we started. We had to prepare for more than a hundred opposing witnesses and more than a hundred witnesses of our own. And, we reviewed hundreds of boxes of documents (hundreds of thousands of pages). Yet, after the case started and throughout the Paxton trial, we were bombarded nightly with boxes of new documents produced by the other side. Even though the deadline for their production was months prior, they continued to dump on us thousands of documents nightly, most of which we had never seen.
